---
import CallToAction from "../components/CallToAction.astro";
import CaseNote from "../components/CaseNote.astro";
import CaseSection from "../components/CaseSection.astro";
import SiteLayout from "../layouts/SiteLayout.astro";

const email = "abeszilagyi@gmail.com";
---

<SiteLayout
  title="About Me | Abraham Szilagyi"
  description="About Abraham Szilagyi, a builder of practical workflow tools for operational friction, agent-assisted development, and daily-use systems."
>
    <main>
      <section class="section page-hero">
        <h1>Navigating Operational Friction</h1>
        <p>
          I turn the work people dread into tools they want to use. Teams
          coordinating across packets, shared folders, spreadsheets, and
          handoffs need practical tools tailored to how their information
          actually moves. These are the kinds of puzzles I like solving:
          mapping the friction, finding the cleaner path, and building
          solutions that meet people where they are.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="section tight">
        <CaseSection title="Designing for Momentum">
            <p>
              My best work happens where tasks get repeated, information gets
              translated, and the next move gets delayed.
            </p>
            <div class="values-grid">
              <CaseNote title="Listen First">
                I start by understanding how the people closest to the problem see the work, before deciding what the system should become.
              </CaseNote>
              <CaseNote title="Find The Cleaner Path">
                I look for where effort piles up, where the current path resists people, and where a simpler shape can emerge.
              </CaseNote>
              <CaseNote title="Build The Bridge">
                I design between the current mess and the cleaner path, with tools that make sense to people who did not build them.
              </CaseNote>
              <CaseNote title="Guide The Landing">
                I keep listening, adjusting, and simplifying until the new way feels like help instead of another system to manage.
              </CaseNote>
            </div>
        </CaseSection>
      </section>

      <section class="section tight">
        <CaseSection title="Built Under Pressure">
            <p>
              I spent years managing live event systems: broadcast, stage
              lighting, sound, and multimedia setups for large audiences.
            </p>
            <p>
              The controls had to be clear under stress, reliable when
              conditions changed, and usable by teams with different levels of
              experience. When a system was expected to work on cue, I learned
              to prepare the fallback before anyone needed it.
            </p>
            <p>
              That is the standard I bring to practical software. I stay close
              to the people doing the work every day, respect the pressure they
              are under, and make the next step easier to trust.
            </p>
        </CaseSection>
      </section>

      <section class="section tight">
        <CaseSection title="Working With Agents">
            <p>
            AI helps me extend my operational discipline and explore more
            solutions through a controlled workflow. I guide agents with clear
            goals, carefully scoped tasks, thoughtful delegation, and critical
            review. The results should be usable faster without becoming harder
            to understand, test, or maintain.
            </p>
            <div class="values-grid">
              <CaseNote title="Accelerate the Process">
                Agents are force multipliers for exploration, implementation,
                testing, and refinement. I stay responsible for defining the
                problem, shaping the constraints, holding the work to clear
                acceptance criteria, and proving the solution can be trusted.
              </CaseNote>
              <CaseNote title="Design for Delegation">
                When a task is well defined, a lighter model can compete with
                an expensive one. Effective delegation is not just cost
                awareness; legible commands, structured tools, focused tasks,
                and clear context reduce wasted time and expensive guesswork.
              </CaseNote>
              <CaseNote title="Make Progress Reusable">
                AI-assisted work can leave behind a confusing trail; I
                prioritize well-documented, coherent systems others can inspect,
                verify, adjust, and extend. Future agents and developers should
                be able to build on what we have already learned.
              </CaseNote>
              <CaseNote title="Use the Right Tool">
                Not every problem needs maximum horsepower. Some tasks are
                boring and mechanical; some need deeper analysis worth getting
                right. I choose the model around the shape of the task, so
                reasoning depth stays connected to the value of the decision
                being made.
              </CaseNote>
            </div>
        </CaseSection>
      </section>

      <CallToAction
        id="workflow-conversation"
        title="Let's talk about what your team needs to make easier."
        buttonText="Email Me"
        copyValue={email}
        copiedText="Copied"
        secondaryHref="/work/"
        secondaryText="Check Out My Work"
      >
        You do not need to know the fix yet. Walk me through where the work
        gets stuck, and we can start there.
      </CallToAction>
    </main>
</SiteLayout>
